1. Introduction

1.1 Background Information

Pulsars are high-magnetized neutron stars that spin at accurately constant speeds (Wikimedia Foundation, 2024). They emit radiation beams from their top and bottom. Because of these unique properties, astronomers can detect radiation pulses as these beams sweep the earth. Since they are spinning with extremely consistent periods, pulsars are frequently used as independent clocks, allowing astronomers to observe fluctuations in spacetime. However, these pulses can be quite difficult to distinguish from the large quantity of background radiation in space, making separating true pulsars from other candidates manually challenging. Therefore, we would like to build a model that can simplify this job with both accuracy and efficiency through this project.

1.2 Research Question

Our research question is:
Which candidate star will be a pulsar? How can we identify a pulsar given its radiation profile with accuracy and efficiency.

1.3 Dataset

We will use HTRU2 dataset (Lyon et al., 2016). to classify pulsar stars. The dataset contains Integrated Profile and DM-SNR curve records for pulsar candidates.

  • Integrated profile is a continuous sequence of measurements that describes the pulse signal received over time.
  • DM-SNR curve is a curve showing the signal-to-noise ratio between the pulse and background radiation emissions with respect to time.

The author of this dataset extracted 4 statistical features for each of these 2 arrays, which produces 8 single variables (mean, standard deviation, kurtosis, and skewness for each of these two arrays). These variables can describe how a potential pulsar spins, how long is one spinning period, how much radiation it emits, etc. With these characteristics, astronomers can tell whether a star is a pulsar or not.

2. Methods & Results

For this project, we will use R language to perform our experiments. Libraries such as Tidyverse and Tidymodels will be used to manipulate the data and build the model. Some key steps of our project are listed below.

  1. Set up a developing environment.
  2. Read the dataset.
  3. Perform data wrangling.
  4. Split training and testing dataset.
  5. Perform basic analysis of the training dataset.
  6. Build the final model with parameter tuning and cross-validation.
  7. Test the model on the training dataset.

2.1.1 Data Wrangling

After the data is read from the source, we need to wrangle it for future analysis. We noticed that the training dataset does not have a proper column name. Instead, all the column names are provided in a separate Readme.txt. Therefore, it will be a lot more comprehensible if we rename all the columns to give them proper column names.

Here is a list of new column names and their corresponding meanings:

  1. profile_mean: mean of integrated profile curve.
  2. profile_sd: standard deviation of integrated profile curve.
  3. profile_kurtosis: kurtosis of integrated profile curve.
  4. profile_skewness: skewness of integrated profile curve.
  5. DM_SNR_mean: mean of DM SNR curve.
  6. DM_SNR_sd: standard deviation of DM SNR curve.
  7. DM_SNR_kurtosis: kurtosis of DM SNR curve.
  8. DN_SNR_skewness: skewness of DM SNR curve.
  9. pulsar_star: whether this observation is a pulsar star or not. (true means it is a pulsar star, and false means it is not.)
In[3]:
# rename the columns according to data/Readme.txt
pulsar_data <- pulsar_data |>
    rename(profile_mean = X1,
          profile_sd = X2,
          profile_kurtosis = X3,
          profile_skewness = X4,
          DM_SNR_mean = X5,
          DM_SNR_sd = X6,
          DM_SNR_kurtosis = X7,
          DM_SNR_skewness = X8,
          pulsar_star = X9) |> 
          # mark the label column as a categorical variable
          mutate(pulsar_star = as_factor(pulsar_star)) |>
          # pulsar_star refers to if the row is a pulsar star or not
          mutate(pulsar_star = fct_recode(pulsar_star, "true" = "1", "false" = "0"))

2.1.4 Resample Training Set

Now, we have collected enough information about the dataset. It is the time to start training the model. We decided to use K-nearest neighbors model to perform the classification task.

Since there is a serious class imbalance in the training set, we need to resample it to balance class labels. To reduce the computational expense in the training process, we decided to use a downsampling strategy. Downsampling will reduce the number of false labels until it has the same number with true labels.

In[10]:
# Downsample the data
downsample_recipe <- recipe(pulsar_star ~ ., data=pulsar_train) |>
    step_downsample(pulsar_star, under_ratio=1) |>
    prep()

pulsar_train_downsampled <- downsample_recipe |>
    bake(new_data=NULL)

2.1.5 Tuning Parameter with Cross-validation

In[11]:
# set up model specification
knn_spec <- nearest_neighbor(weight_func="rectangular", neighbors=tune()) |>
    set_mode("classification") |>
    set_engine("kknn")
# set up a recipe that also normalizes the data.
knn_recipe <- recipe(pulsar_star ~ ., data=pulsar_train_downsampled) |>
    step_center(all_predictors()) |>
    step_scale(all_predictors())
In[12]:
# vfold model
pulsar_vfold <- vfold_cv(pulsar_train_downsampled, v = 5, strata = pulsar_star)

# K values to try
kvals <- tibble(neighbors=1:10)

# set up a workflow that assembles recipe and model
tuning_result <- workflow() |>
    add_recipe(knn_recipe) |>
    add_model(knn_spec) |>
    tune_grid(resamples=pulsar_vfold, grid=kvals) |>
    collect_metrics()
cat("Table 10: The Most Accurate Model in Tuning")
tuning_result |>
    filter(.metric=="accuracy") |>
    arrange(desc(mean)) |>
    slice(1)

2.1.6 Build Final Model

In[14]:
# pull the final k value
k <- tuning_result |>
    filter(.metric=="accuracy") |>
    arrange(desc(mean)) |>
    slice(1) |>
    pull(neighbors)

# final knn model
final_knn_spec <- nearest_neighbor(neighbor=k, weight_func="rectangular") |>
    set_mode("classification") |>
    set_engine("kknn")

final_model <- workflow() |>
    add_model(final_knn_spec) |>
    add_recipe(knn_recipe) |>
    fit(data = pulsar_train_downsampled)

3. Discussion

3.1 Summary

When beginning this project, the initial research question that was posed was how we identify what candidate stars could be pulsars, and how we can identify a pulsar given its radiation profile. We used the HTRU2 dataset to classify our pulsar stars. The first thing we did was wrangle and clean our initial dataset in order to provide readable column names to our data and allow filtering for the pulsar_star column by transforming it into a categorical variable. We divided our training and testing subsets accordingly and then resampled our training set in order to remove model bias. This was necessary as the amount of false observations was significantly larger than the amount of true observations in our training set. We then normalized our predictor values as there was a large range of values before feeding the data to our model. In order to properly take advantage of the K-nearest neighbors model to classify stars as pulsar or not, we decided to downsample our training set to prevent a major class imbalance.

When visualizing our tuning result (Figure 2), we found that setting K=9 to train our model led to an accuracy of 92.9% for cross-validation.

After testing the performance of this model on the testing set, we can observe in our confusion matrix (Figure 3) that there was a relatively low number of false positives and false negatives allowing for accuracy to be above 95% (Table 12). Because the accuracy found when using our model against test data was higher than the cross-validation data, it indicates that our model can generalize very well and can perform with a very high degree of accuracy on data it has never seen before.

Since precision is calculated by $\frac{\text{TP}}{\text{TP} + \text{FP}}$, where $TP$ means true positive, and $FP$ means false positive, this metric "reports how many of the positive predictions the classifier made were actually positive"(Timbers et al., 2022). Our model has a precision of 98.8%, which proves our model is very trustworthy and accurate in identifying true pulsars.

On the other hand, our model has a recall of 96.2%, which is calculated by $\frac{\text{TP}}{\text{TP} + \text{FN}}$ ($TP$ stands for true positive, and $FN$ stands for false negative) (Timbers et al., 2022). This high recall value means that our model will hardly miss any potential true pulsars. This is beneficial for astronomers since pulsars are hard to find and we don't want to miss any possibilities of finding a true pulsar.

3.2 Alignment with Expectations

Our model is designed to identify pulsars based on the integrated profile and the DM-SNR curve of stars. Specifically, the dataset provided us with the mean, skewness, standard deviation, and kurtosis features of these two metrics. Considering the fact that we are able to achieve a higher accuracy when using our model against test data than it achieved when cross-validating, it is safe to say that we achieved our goal. We were able to achieve a 92.9% accuracy when cross-validating our model and a 95.5% accuracy when using our model against test data, showing that our group was properly able to create a model that effectively generalizes beyond the initial training dataset, exhibiting strong predictive capabilities in unseen scenarios.

3.3 Impact of Findings

The instruments used to identify pulsar candidates provide researchers with large quantities of data that can be difficult to sort through (Zhang et al., 2020). Manual screening of the data can be quite inefficient, which is why classification models (such as the one above) are a better choice for the task.

Our analysis found that the model we created to classify potential pulsars has an accuracy of 95.5%. This allows for the majority of potential pulsars to be correctly classified as such. A high accuracy is important as knowing the location of new pulsars can allow for more accurate recognition and a greater understanding of bodies in space. This can lead to insights regarding gravity and general relativity. Additionally, pulsars can provide information on the formation of black holes and the location of neighboring planets.

According to our confusion matrix (Figure 3), the number of true predictions in our test data set was over 10 times greater than the number of false predictions, suggesting that only a small percent of pulsar candidates are identified as pulsars. This reaffirms the importance of creating models such as the one shown above in order to narrow down the number of candidates. Knowing which pulsar candidates are actual pulsars is crucial to the study of these stars and our understanding of the universe.

  2. Can we further subcategorize pulsars based on their characteristics and this dataset?
